main event: Two bright light objects were observed in the sky over Salineville, Ohio on November 7, 1956. They appeared to be larger than stars and were seen at very high altitudes. The objects were stationary and observed for several minutes.
interesting points: The sighting was classified as 'astronomical in nature' based on the descriptions, durations, and flight paths of the objects.
The report mentions that the flight path of the object indicated it was probably caused by an aircraft, although the object was observed as stationary.
There were no photographs taken during the observation.
The source of the report was a civilian sighting.
The duration of the observation was described as 'one long' indicating a relatively extended sighting.
sighted object: two bright light objects at very high altitudes
